fields.title: The French Dispatch of the Liberty, Kansas Evening Sun
fields.review: A loving ode to the spirit of journalism, The French Dispatch will be most enjoyed by fans of Wes Anderson's meticulously arranged aesthetic. It can be a little hard to follow, but if you're a fan of Wes Anderson's filmmaking, you won't want to miss it.

fields.title: Don't Worry Darling
fields.review: Despite an intriguing array of talent on either side of the camera, Don't Worry Darling is a mostly muddled rehash of overly familiar themes.

fields.title: Divergent
fields.review: With an adherence to YA formula that undercuts its individualistic message, Divergent opens its planned trilogy in disappointingly predictable fashion.

fields.title: The Mortal Instruments: City of Bones
fields.review: The Mortal Instruments: City of Bones borrows ingredients from seemingly every fantasy franchise of the last 30 years -- but can't seem to figure out what to do with them.

fields.title: Interstellar
fields.review: Interstellar represents more of the thrilling, thought-provoking, and visually resplendent filmmaking moviegoers have come to expect from writer-director Christopher Nolan, even if its intellectual reach somewhat exceeds its grasp.

fields.title: Little Women (2019)
fields.review: With a stellar cast and a smart, sensitive retelling of its classic source material, Greta Gerwig's Little Women proves some stories truly are timeless.

fields.title: Pride and Prejudice (2005)
fields.review: Sure, it's another adaptation of cinema's fave Jane Austen novel, but key performances and a modern filmmaking sensibility make this familiar period piece fresh and enjoyable.

fields.title: The Grand Budapest Hotel
fields.review: Typically stylish but deceptively thoughtful, The Grand Budapest Hotel finds Wes Anderson once again using ornate visual environments to explore deeply emotional ideas.

fields.title: Emma (2020)
fields.review: Other adaptations may do a better job of consistently capturing the spirit of the classic source material, but Jane Austen fans should still find a solid match in this Emma.

fields.title: The King (2019)
fields.review: While The King is sometimes less than the sum of its impressive parts, strong source material and gripping performances make this a period drama worth hailing.
